        "trailText":"<p>Join our expert panel on Tuesday 5 November between 12.30 and 2.30pm to explore ideas for transforming care at home</p>",
        "headline":"Live discussion: improving homecare",
        "body":"<p>The <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-22435095\" title=\"\">squeeze on social care budgets</a> and increasing demographic pressures have put the homecare system under strain. A survey exploring attitudes to homecare in England, conducted by the Guardian Social Care Network and the Department of Health, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/oct/30/homecare-cuts-home-visits-older-disabled-people\">uncovered some shocking stories of poor and unacceptable care</a>.</p><p>The survey, of care workers, homecare providers, council workers and service users and their families, revealed that many people receiving care are happy with the individuals who provide support, though more have misgivings about the homecare system as a whole. Time constraints, low pay and lack of training <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/social-care-network/2013/oct/30/main-challenges-homecare-survey-findings\" title=\"\">were found to be the main challenges facing frontline care staff</a>. The top three most important factors in offering good homecare were identified as sufficient time for care, friendly, respectful, capable care workers and choice about services.</p><p>The survey asked for ideas about how to make the service better and respondents offered plenty of suggestions. These ranged from an online grocery shop model of booking homecare slots to local care teams in every community so that people know their care workers. Another suggestion was for care workers to have tablet devices to allow more time with the person receiving care and to share information with the family doctor or nurse if appropriate.</p><p>Join us between 12.30 and 2.30pm on Tuesday 5 November when we will discuss these ideas and explore how to improve homecare. Our expert panel will consider the findings of the survey and ask: how can we transform these ideas into practice? How can we spread great homecare across the UK? If you have a question you'd like to ask the panel, you can email it to socialcare@theguardian.com. You can also tweet us your questions at <a href=\"https://twitter.com/GdnSocialCare\" title=\"\">@GdnSocialCare</a>.</p><h2>The panel so far includes</h2><p>• <strong>Norman Lamb</strong>, minister for care and support<br />• <strong>Jon Rouse</strong>, director general for social care, local government and care partnerships at the <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-of-health\" title=\"\">Department of Health</a><br />• <strong>Bridget Warr</strong>, chief executive of the <a href=\"http://www.ukhca.co.uk/index.aspx\" title=\"\">United Kingdom Homecare Association</a><br />• <strong>Alan Long,</strong> an executive director of <a href=\"http://www.mearsgroup.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Mears Group</a>, a provider of homecare<br />• <strong>Clare Pelham</strong>, chief executive of <a href=\"http://www.lcdisability.org/\" title=\"\">Leonard Cheshire Disability</a><br />• <strong>Sarah Pickup,</strong> director of adult care service at <a href=\"http://www.hertsdirect.org/\" title=\"\">Hertfordshire county council </a>and former president of the <a href=\"http://www.adass.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=frontpage&amp;Itemid=1\" title=\"\">Association of Directors of Adult Social Services</a><br />• <strong>Sally Percival</strong>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/social-care-network-department-of-health-partner/personal-budgets-positive-impact-lives\" rel=\"nofollow\">whose mother and son have personal budgets</a><br />•<strong> Jan O' Leary</strong>,<strong> </strong><strong> </strong>who receives homecare services<strong>. </strong>She is a former senior nursing manager<br />• <strong>Emily Holzhausen</strong>, director of policy and public affairs<strong> </strong>at <a href=\"http://www.carersuk.org/\" title=\"\">Carers UK</a><br />• <strong>Alan Rosenbach</strong>, special policy lead at the <a href=\"http://www.cqc.org.uk/\">Care Quality Commission</a><br />• <strong>Councillor Gillian Ford</strong>, vice chair of the Local Government Association's Community Wellbeing Board</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421281194|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|25f5bbcdc91b92fed4563ea6e8bac91299a249f8 -->",
