      "id":"social-care-network/2013/oct/30/main-challenges-homecare-survey-findings",
      "sectionId":"social-care-network",
      "sectionName":"Social Care Network",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-30T08:10:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Time, pay and lack of training are main challenges for homecare staff",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/social-care-network/2013/oct/30/main-challenges-homecare-survey-findings",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/social-care-network/2013/oct/30/main-challenges-homecare-survey-findings",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>A major survey, conducted by the Guardian Social Care Network and the Department of Health, reveals attitudes to homecare</p>",
        "headline":"Time, pay and lack of training are main challenges for homecare staff",
        "body":"<p>Time constraints, low pay and lack of training for frontline staff are the key challenges facing care workers in England, according to a <a href=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/ni/1383067901570/Homecare-survey-full-result.pdf\" title=\"\">survey on homecare</a>.</p><p>Some 73% of respondents to the survey, conducted by the Guardian Social Care Network and the Department of Health, cited a lack of time as the major challenge for care workers who make home visits, while 67% cited pay and conditions, and 56% said insufficient training.</p><p>More than 1,440 people took part in the survey on attitudes to homecare, including homecare providers, care workers, people who receive homecare and their friends and relatives.</p><p>The survey was carried out following <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/social-care-network/2013/jul/03/solving-problems-poor-homecare\" title=\"\">the launch of the \"homecare innovation challenge\" this summer</a>. The project aims to tackle the problems of the homecare sector and transform the service.</p><p>The top three most important factors in offering good homecare were identified as sufficient time for care (59%), friendly, respectful, capable care workers (58%) and choice about services (43%). And the main challenges facing organisations that provide care were cited as too few fully trained care workers, council commissioning and a shortage of care workers.</p><p>When asked what would improve homecare, many said improving the recruitment, training and monitoring of new and existing staff. \"Homecare needs to be seen as a skilled career rather than a job that fills the gap,\" said one respondent. Others stressed the importance of the relationship between the care worker and the person receiving homecare. One said: \"Having the same responsible and respectful person deliver the care regularly to ensure that a relationship develops between the parties so that each person values the other.\"</p><p>And another wrote: \"Allow sufficient time for people receiving care to be treated as people, not 'tasks to be done'.\"</p><p>Other suggestions involved making more information about services available. \"The problem I have experienced is that information needed regarding service providers (private, PAs, etc) is not easily accessible for those that need it, ie the clients and their families,\" one person commented.</p><p>Respondents also offered their ideas for improving homecare: \"There needs to be tighter focus on regular reviewing of clients to ensure the care agreed upon is provided,\" one wrote. Another suggested: \"Make it locality based – the smaller the catchment area the more likely to build a reputation and relationship with the local community.\"</p><p>Some 44% of homecare providers who responded to the survey said they didn't think councils worked well with others to arrange good quality homecare.</p><p>When asked about their experiences of homecare, 46% of respondents reported a positive experience with individual care staff, compared with 15% who said their experience was negative. But 39% said their experience of local authorities assessing their needs and arranging care was poor or very poor, compared with just 17% who thought it was good or very good.</p><p><em>Click </em><a href=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/ni/1383067901570/Homecare-survey-full-result.pdf\" title=\"\"><em>here for the full report on the survey's findings</em></a></p><p><strong>Why not join our community? Becoming a member of the </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/social-care-network\" title=\"\"><strong>Guardian Social Care Network</strong></a><strong> means you get sent weekly email updates on policy and best practice in the sector, as well as exclusive offers. </strong><a href=\"https://register.theguardian.com/social-care/\" title=\"\"><strong>Sign up for free here</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421207181|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|d7aedf9c2b3cd449735877df4862bf52e4290b47 -->",
